snippet.textDisplay: M. Markle is not alone in not knowing with full clarity  what you will experience when you marry.  However, the life that she was about to accept is one that has been documented for centuries and is hardly lacking on history and information as to its traditions and restrictions.  In life, love and marriage you make a promise and a commitment, not knowing exactly what is ahead but fully understanding that regardless of your feelings at any given time,  you will endeavor with every fiber of your being to honor the promise you made and understand that it is about something far greater than  your own immediate desires.  You certainly don't  accept the opportunity of a lifetime, millions upon millions of dollars worth of benefits such as security, an internationally celebrated state wedding state wedding, the enthusiastic welcome of millions of citizens wishing you the very best with great affection as you represent their country and then in a mere 20 months announce  "it isn't working" for you.  Truly great people don't approach life with the idea to quit things that are challenging when suddenly you feel it is different than what you imagined.  The experience of high school, being a good parent, getting your college degree, doing well in a job means commitment well beyond a trial period.  To not consider difficult times in this way will result in disappointment for those closest to you and well beyond because  you've basically failed to honor others and in doing so, fail yourself as an exceptional human being.

If Mr. and Mrs. Sussex (if that's the name they take) want a life in quiet isolation, perhaps they should consider re-locating to the Falkland Islands in the south Atlantic. It's British territory, with a large military presence, no close neighbors, and no TV news.

But no, they're going to settle "somewhere in Canada." I'm betting that they won't be looking for a place in Ft. MacMurray, or Whitehorse, or Yellowknife, or Winnipeg, or 100-Mile House, or Red Lake, or St. Johns, or anywhere that actually has real people who live and work in real winter much of the year (i.e. most of the country). No, they'll probably receive a prime chunk of ocean-front property near Tofino on Vancouver Island, or in the Kitsilano waterfront in Vancouver, with security provided 24/7 by Canadian taxpayers.
They'll never get a bill for power, or heat, or water, and they'll have food and staff brought in after being inspected, all on the taxpayer's dime. No driving to the store for groceries, or taking the kids to school. But, our "woke" far-left government, elected to form a minority Parliament by voters in only 2 of Canada's 10 Provinces, will pony up. 'Why' we should is a question nobody is answering.
